        <h2>What is pickleball?</h2>
        <p>Pickleball is a paddle sport that combines elements of tennis, badminton, and ping-pong. Played on a court with similar dimensions to a doubles badminton court, pickleball utilizes a perforated plastic ball and solid paddles made of wood or composite materials. The game is typically played in doubles format, though singles play is also common. Players serve underhand and must allow the ball to bounce once on each side before volleys are permitted. Pickleball emphasizes both finesse and power, requiring players to strategically place shots while maintaining quick reflexes. The sport's quirky name has several origin stories, one of which involves the founders' dog, Pickles, who chased after errant balls during the game's early development. With its simple rules, fast-paced action, and accessibility to players of all ages and skill levels, pickleball has gained widespread popularity in recent years, becoming a beloved pastime in communities around the world.</p>
    </div>

